    <h2>What Problems Does a Weighted Blanket Actually Solve?</h2>
    <p>Weighted blankets aren't magic, but they target specific sleep issues. Here's what the science supports and what this knitted design solves better than traditional bead-filled models:</p>
    <table class="problem-solution-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Sleep Problem</th>
          <th>How Weighted Blankets Help</th>
          <th>Why This Knitted Model Wins</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Racing mind / anxiety at bedtime</td>
          <td>Deep pressure stimulation activates the parasympathetic nervous system, lowering cortisol and signaling safety to your brain.</td>
          <td>The breathable knit doesn't trap heat like dense bead blankets, so you stay calm without overheating. Less fidgeting = better pressure effect.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Taking 45+ minutes to fall asleep</td>
          <td>The weighted pressure can reduce sleep latency (time to fall asleep) by 5–15 minutes for people sensitive to deep touch.</td>
          <td>Chunky knit distributes weight evenly without cold spots or bunching, so the calming effect feels consistent across your whole body.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Frequent nighttime waking or restlessness</td>
          <td>Continuous pressure helps anchor your nervous system, reducing micro-arousals and keeping you in deeper sleep stages.</td>
          <td>No glass beads means less noise when you shift position, and no risk of beads pooling in one corner. Stays even throughout the night.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- §9 "What is..." Section -->
  <section class="what-is-section">
    <h2>What Makes a Knitted Weighted Blanket Different From Bead-Filled?</h2>
    <p>Traditional weighted blankets pack tiny glass or plastic beads into fabric pockets to add weight. They're cheap to produce ($40–80) and therapeutic. But they have downsides: beads migrate to corners, make crunching sounds, feel cold to the touch, and aren't machine washable without risking leaks.</p>
    <p>The LAGRATY knitted model replaces beads entirely with yarn weight—think of a chunky-knit throw where the thickness and density of the yarn itself provides the pressure. Benefits:</p>
    <ul class="benefit-list">
      <li><strong>Breathable:</strong> Knit fabric has air pockets. You don't overheat like you do under dense bead blankets.</li>
      <li><strong>Silent:</strong> No beads shifting means no crunching sounds when you roll over. Stays quiet all night.</li>
      <li><strong>Machine Washable:</strong> Toss the whole blanket in cold water. No disassembly, no fear of bead leaks.</li>
      <li><strong>Pet Safe:</strong> If your dog or cat chews it (unlikely, but possible), there are no loose beads to ingest.</li>
      <li><strong>Even Weight Distribution:</strong> The yarn weight is woven in uniformly, so you get consistent pressure everywhere—no cold spots.</li>
      <li><strong>Aesthetic:</strong> Looks like a designer throw blanket you'd drape over a couch. Works as decor, not just a therapeutic tool.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The downside: this design is expensive to produce. You're paying $290 for the engineering, not economy of scale. A bead-filled 7lbs blanket costs half as much.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- §10 Who Should Buy -->
