    <h2>Who Should Buy This (And Who Shouldn't)</h2>

    <div class="pros-cons">
      <div class="buy-if">
        <h3>✓ Buy If You…</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Weigh 80–160 lbs and find 7 lbs of pressure genuinely calming (not too light, not overwhelming)</li>
          <li>Want a weighted blanket that doubles as room decor—the chunky knit looks intentionally designer</li>
          <li>Have pets (cats, dogs) in bed and worry about loose beads</li>
          <li>Hate the crunchy sound of bead-filled blankets shifting at night</li>
          <li>Value machine washability and don't want to fuss with sealing or dry cleaning</li>
          <li>Sleep hot and need a breathable weighted option</li>
          <li>Are willing to spend premium price for a unique product concept</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="skip-if">
        <h3>✗ Skip If You…</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Weigh over 200 lbs—7 lbs will feel too light for therapeutic benefit. You need 10–15 lbs minimum.</li>
          <li>Are on a strict budget. Standard bead blankets work just as well for half the price.</li>
          <li>Prefer maximum pressure. Knitted blankets feel gentler; if you need a "crushing" sensation, go 15+ lbs.</li>
          <li>Live in a hot climate. Knit is breathable, but it's still a full blanket on top of you.</li>
          <li>Want the most scientifically tested option. Bead-filled blankets have longer clinical track records.</li>
          <li>Prefer minimal aesthetic. You want pure function, not a decorative throw.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

